pdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/kaduyskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Ivanovskoye''' ({{lang-ru|\u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nikolskoye Rural Settlement, [[Kaduysky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 4 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref> \n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Kaduy, Vologda Oblast|Kaduy]] is 28&nbsp;km, to Nikolskoye is 4&nbsp;km. Vasilyevskaya is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Kaduysky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Kaduysky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ivanovskoye,_Kaduysky_District,_Vologda_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Herne", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''Thomas Herne''' (died 1722) was an English academic and lay participant in religious controversy.\n\n==Life==\nA native of [[Suffolk]], he was admitted as a pensioner at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]],<ref>{{acad|HN711T|Herne, Thomas}}</ref> on 29 October 1711. In the following year he was elected to a scholarship, graduated B.A. in 1715, and was incorporated at Oxford 21 February 1716. Not long afterwards the Duchess of Bedford made him tutor to her sons [[Wriothesley Russell, 3rd Duke of Bedford|Wriothesley]] and [[John Russell, 4th Duke of Bedford|John]], later successively the third and fourth Dukes of Bedford. In 1716 Herne was elected to a vacant fellowship at [[Merton College, Oxford]], and on 11 October 1718 proceeded M.A. He died a layman and unmarried, at Woburn Abbey, Bedfordshire, in 1722.\n\n==Works==\nHerne took part in the [[Bangorian controversy]], and published under the pseudonym \u2018Phileleutherus Cantabrigiensis:\u2019\n\n*\u2018The False Notion of a Christian Priesthood,\u2019 &c., in answer to [[William Law]], 1717\u201318; \n*\u2018Three Discourses on Private Judgment against the Authority of the Magistrate over Conscience, and Considerations concerning uniting Protestants, translated from Professor Werenfels, with a preface to Dr. Tenison,\u2019 London, 1718, translating [[Samuel Werenfels]];\n*\u2018An Essay on Imposing and Subscribing Articles of Religion,\u2019 1719; and \n*\u2018A Letter to Dr. Mangey, on his Sermon upon Christ's Divinity,\u2019 1719. To [[Thomas Mangey]].\n\nHe also wrote:\n\n*\u2018A Letter to the Prolocutor, in Answer to one from him to Dr. Tenison,\u2019 1718, in support of [[Edward Tenison]]; \n*\u2018A Letter to the Rev. Dr. Tenison concerning Citations out of Archbishop Wake's Preliminary Discourse to the Apostolic Fathers,\u2019 London, 1718; \n*\u2018A Vindication of the Archbishop of Canterbury from being the author of \u201cA Letter on the State of Religion in England,\u201d printed at Zurich,\u2019 London, 1719; and \n*\u2018A second Letter to Dr. Mangey,\u2019 by \u2018A Seeker after Truth,\u2019 on his sermon on Christ's eternal existence, 1719, under the pseudonym of \u2018Philanagnostes Criticus.\u2019\n\nHerne issued in 1719 an account of all the major pamphlets issued in the Bangorian controversy to the end of 1718; a continuation of this account to the end of 1719, London, 1720; and a reissue of the whole, London, 1720.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Herne, Thomas}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Herne, Thomas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herne, Thomas}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1722 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''Thomas Herne''' (died 1722) was an English academic and lay participant in religious controversy.\n\n==Life==\nA native of [[Suffolk]], he was admitted as a pensioner at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]],<ref>{{acad|HN711T|Herne, Thomas}}</ref> on 29 October 1711. In the following year he was elected to a scholarship, graduated B.A. in 1715, and was incorporated at Oxford 21 February 1716. Not long afterwards the Duchess of Bedford made him tutor to her sons [[Wriothesley Russell, 3rd Duke of Bedford|Wriothesley]] and [[John Russell, 4th Duke of Bedford|John]], later successively the third and fourth Dukes of Bedford. In 1716 Herne was elected to a vacant fellowship at [[Merton College, Oxford]], and on 11 October 1718 proceeded M.A. He died a layman and unmarried, at Woburn Abbey, Bedfordshire, in 1722.\n\n==Works==\nHerne took part in the [[Bangorian controversy]], and published under the pseudonym \u2018Phileleutherus Cantabrigiensis:\u2019\n\n*\u2018The False Notion of a Christian Priesthood,\u2019 &c., in answer to [[William Law]], 1717\u201318; \n*\u2018Three Discourses on Private Judgment against the Authority of the Magistrate over Conscience, and Considerations concerning uniting Protestants, translated from Professor Werenfels, with a preface to Dr. Tenison,\u2019 London, 1718, translating [[Samuel Werenfels]];\n*\u2018An Essay on Imposing and Subscribing Articles of Religion,\u2019 1719; and \n*\u2018A Letter to Dr. Mangey, on his Sermon upon Christ's Divinity,\u2019 1719. To [[Thomas Mangey]].\n\nHe also wrote:\n\n*\u2018A Letter to the Prolocutor, in Answer to one from him to Dr. Tenison,\u2019 1718, in support of [[Edward Tenison]]; \n*\u2018A Letter to the Rev. Dr. Tenison concerning Citations out of Archbishop Wake's Preliminary Discourse to the Apostolic Fathers,\u2019 London, 1718; \n*\u2018A Vindication of the Archbishop of Canterbury from being the author of \u201cA Letter on the State of Religion in England,\u201d printed at Zurich,\u2019 London, 1719; and \n*\u2018A second Letter to Dr. Mangey,\u2019 by \u2018A Seeker after Truth,\u2019 on his sermon on Christ's eternal existence, 1719, under the pseudonym of \u2018Philanagnostes Criticus.\u2019\n\nHerne issued in 1719 an account of all the major pamphlets issued in the Bangorian controversy to the end of 1718; a continuation of this account to the end of 1719, London, 1720; and a reissue of the whole, London, 1720.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Herne, Thomas}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Herne, Thomas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herne, Thomas}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n[[Category:1722 deaths]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:18th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:18th-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Herne"}
