ain to be paid at the end of each month.\n\tThe Sergeant Major was probably Lord Loudoun\u2019s own sergeant, Robert Grant, recruited on 10th May 1746. He doubtless had service in some other Regiment. He would receive one shilling a day extra, or \u00a31.10 a month extra.\n\tBy October 1747 there were records of 28 sergeants in nine companies. Five of the sergeants had been appointed in 1747, and one had been promoted from being a corporal.\n\n'''Corporals in Lord Loudoun's Regiment'''\n\tThirty corporals were recorded in eleven companies in 1746. Of these nine were recruited in 1745.There were ten new corporals by 1747, one a promoted private.\n\n'''Drummers and pipers in Lord Loudoun's Regiment'''\n        There were records of 22 drummers and four pipers.\n\tDonald Ban MacCrummen, piper to Captain John MacLeod's company, was not recorded. He was killed at the Rout of Moy in February 1746. Captain MacLeod had great difficulty in finding a replacement, but eventually, in March 1747, Lieutenant Donald MacDonald, stationed at Glenelg, wrote[135] that he had \u201clisted a good piper for the Grandr Company.\u201d He was Neil McCartan or MacArthur, from the Trotternish piping family.\n\tIn December 1746 John Campbell was the piper in the Lieutenant Colonel\u2019s company, as was Kenneth McKenzie, in the Major's. Duncan McPharling, from Dumbarton, aged 21, was piper in Captain Archibald Macnab\u2019s company, and Finlay Ferguson, from Tarbert, Argyll, was piper in Captain Grant\u2019s company, formerly Captain Alexander Campbell\u2019s company. John Mackleod in Captain Sutherland's company may have been a piper but left the Regiment. Alexander Bruce of Captain Archibald Macnab's company may have been a piper. \n\tThe Colonel recruited John Bain, from Canongate in Edinburgh, in August 1746 and he was appointed Drum Major. On 2nd January 1747 Lord Loudoun gave orders136 for regulatory extra allowance for the Sergeant Major and the Drum Major at 1d a day from each Captain to be paid at the end of each month. For the Drum Major 1 \u00bd d per week for each drum & \u00bd guinea for teaching each young Drum.\n\nReferences:\n1: 21. Dalrymple, John, Earl of Stair, London, 3 May 1745, to Lord Loudoun, LO7647. \n2: 1. SP /186/37 and WO 26/20/255, 1 May 1745.\n3: 22. SP /186/37 and WO 26/20/255, 1May 1745. Great Britain, Army, Lord Loudoun\u2019s Regiment, 1 May 1745, LO10131 B. Copy attested as correct by Lord Loudoun.\n4. Great Britain, Army, Captain\u2019s commission, Earl of Loudoun, 18 Feb 1734. LO 11607. \n5. Great Britain, Army, Capt of the Garrison, Earl of Loudoun, 9 May 1743. LO 11608.\n6. Great Britain, Army, Aid de Camp to the King, Earl of Loudoun, 27 June 1743 (O.S.). LO 11609.\n7. Cope, Sir John, Edinburgh, 31 July 1745, LO10987.\n8. Stuart, Capt John. Return of Lord Loudoun\u2019s Regiments, Aberdeen, 12 Sep 1745. LO12683.\n9. Lord Loudoun\u2019s account of the Battle of Prestonpans, sent to Sir John Cope in October 1745 survives as an annex to \u201cA Report of the Proceedings and Opinion of the Board of General officers, on their Examination into the Conduct, Behaviour and the proceedings of Lieutenant-General Sir John Cope, Knight of the Bath, Colonel Peregrine Lascelles and Brigadier-General Thomas Fowke\u201d edited by B Robins and published in Dublin in 1749.\n10. Campbell, John, Lord Loudoun, LO11786. Newcastle 3 Oct 1745 to William Wilkinson.\n11. Noble, Capt John, Dumbarton, 26 Dec 1745, to Maj Gen John Campbell. NLS 3733/65\n12. Campbell, John, Lord Loudoun. 12 March 1746. Dornoch to Sir John Cope. LO11789\n13. Mann, John, Account for Cloathing. LO12215.\n14. Seton, James, Edinburgh, Account 2 Aug 1745-29 Apr 1746, LO12597. Edinburgh, 14 May 1746. Edinburgh to Lord Loudoun. LO12584. Edinburgh, 16 Dec 1746, correctly 1745. Account for cloathing, LO12598.\n15. Goode, Benjamin. 9 Dec 1745. Account. LO11622. Reeves, Robert. 10 Nov. Particular of arms. LO12477\n16. Dalrymple, Hew, Lord Drummore. 16 Jan 1746. LO11340.\n17